</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=naladini>naladini</A> at: 12/4/02 7:12:05 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=darkerplanes>DarkerPlanes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#333333>(12/5/02 7:42:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=48>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: History of Republicans </span><hr size=1> Silverblade, you are absolutely right, the Republican party was not originally formed as a right-wing &quot;rich man's&quot; party in the very beginning.  <br>
<br>
The roots of the Republicans party can be traced back to the dissolution of the Whig party back in the 1850s when many of its members divided over the issue of slavery,  broke with the Whig (thus effectivly disbanding the party) and founded the Republican party on one platform: to keep slavery OUT of the territories (non-state US posessions).  The original Republican party was actually a One Issue Third Party.  It is the only such party in US history that has ever managed to elevate itself from a third party to a primary party.  <br>
<br>
The roots of the Democrats on the other hand can be traced to the 1830s (making it older than the Republican Party).  Andrew Jackson, disgusted with the National Republicans, split away from the party and formed his own splinter party, calling it the &quot;Democrats&quot;.  Jackson would then go on to win the next two elections for presidency, distinguishing his administration with the creation of a strong, independent presidency through judicious use of his veto power, and the destruction of the National Bank.<br>
<br>
The distinction of the GOP's (Grand Old Party, aka the Republican Party) &quot;conservative&quot; platform as opposed to the Democrat's &quot;liberal&quot; platform really arose in the 1880s-1890s during the Progressive movement launched initially by Democrats (but later continued by Republicans).  During this time, the Republican party was seen as the champion of Big Business, the Gold Standard (which helped big business), and the Middle Class, due to the fact that many of their supporters in the preceeding years had been of those backgrounds. <br>
<br>
The Democrats on the other hand, disgraced and in political trouble following the Civil War (widespread belief, not totally untrue, that Democrats had really been the &quot;Confederates&quot; of the Civil War), sought to adopt a new platform with which to challange the GOP for political supremecy.  Willam Jennings Bryon, the &quot;Great Commoner&quot;, led the Democrats to the championing of the lower classes and non Big Business in his &quot;Cross of Gold&quot; speech against McKinly's gold standard in the 1890s.  <br>
<br>
Thus, by the 1890s the political battle lines had been drawn, the Republicans stood with Business and Middle Class, while the Democrats stood with Labor and the Lower Class.  These battle lines, while blurred today, still exist.  <br>
<br>
Dark<br>
