<br>
&quot;that your [sic]comparing a [sic]economic system(capitalism) to a political system(socialism) its[sic] obvious that theres [sic]alot [sic]of people who really don't know what there[sic] talking about.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
Socialism defined:<br>
<br>
&quot;Any of various theories or systems of social organization in which the means of producing and distributing goods is owned collectively or by a centralized government that often plans and controls the economy.&quot;<br>
<br>
Capitalism defined:<br>
<br>
&quot;An economic system in which the means of production and distribution are privately or corporately owned and development is proportionate to the accumulation and reinvestment of profits gained in a free market.&quot;<br>
<br>
(definitions from www.dictionary.com)<br>
<br>
Whether you call them economic or political, it is obvious that socialism and capitalism are logically opposed, and can be effectively contrasted to one another.<br>
<br>
Cerios continues:<br>
<br>
&quot;I should also point out that the statment &quot;competition brings out the best&quot; is farceical to the point of stupidity, the only place where I have even heard anyone able to give a plausable example of that is sports and I won't go into have assine that it would be to compare sports to life.&quot;<br>
<br>
I think I can offer an example of competition between businesses bringing out the best (for the consumer) in them.  <br>
<br>
I bought a washing machine last month.  There were three area stores I considered buying it from.  I didn't buy from the first store because they had provided poor service in the past on another appliance.  The other two stores both carried the washing machine I wanted and both had good reputations for service.  I went to the second store and got a price quoted to me.  I went to the third and told the clerk the price I'd been quoted at the second; he made a call, and told me he could beat that price by a considerable margin.  I handed him a check.  I got my new washing machine at an excellent price, was treated well, and I know that if the product turns out to be defective it will be repaired or replaced. <br>
<br>
If there had been only one store to choose from (i.e. no competition), they could have given me any price, and provided no service at all post-purchase.  They could have offered only a few products, none of which fit my needs exactly.  But I'd have had no choice but to buy from them if I wanted to avoid stinky drawers.  <br>
<br>
Competition attunes businesses to the consumer's needs.  Businesses have to maintain high standards of quality and low prices, or their competitors will wipe them out.<br>
<br>
