<br>
Socialism is a system under which each individual is rewarded for there work to the extent possible, and that no one individual can or should be rewarded unduly for the work of another.<br>
<br>
And I do find it humorous how you took the definition of Socialism as defined in one segment and left out the following.<br>
<br>
&quot;<br>
The stage in Marxist-Leninist theory intermediate between capitalism and communism, in which collective ownership of the economy under the dictatorship of the proletariat has not yet been successfully achieved. <br>
&quot;<br>
<br>
or how about this definition<br>
<br>
&quot;<br>
[Socialism] was first applied in England to Owen's theory of social reconstruction, and in France to those also of St. Simon and Fourier . . . The word, however, is used with a great variety of meaning, . . . even by economists and learned critics. The general tendency is to regard as socialistic any interference undertaken by society on behalf of the poor, . . . radical social reform which disturbs the present system of private property . . . The tendency of the present socialism is more and more to ally itself with the most advanced democracy. --Encyc. Brit.<br>
&quot;<br>
<br>
(Please note I am rather ambivalent on the topic, your attack forced me into this position)<br>
<br>
The definition that has become popular as of late is due to the rather extreme slant that the world has taken towards capitalism. Socialism is NOT communism as the definition you post would CLEARLY indicate.<br>
<br>
As for capitalism, while that definition is once again rather amusing and grossly inaccurate.<br>
<br>
&quot;<br>
Laissez faire capitalism means the complete separation of economy and state, just like the separation of church and state. Capitalism is the social system based upon private ownership of the means of production which entails a completely uncontrolled and unregulated economy where all land is privately owned. But the separation of the state and the economy is not a primary, it is only an aspect of the premise that capitalism is based upon: individual rights. Capitalism is the only politico-economic system based on the doctrine of individual rights. This means that capitalism recognizes that each and every person is the owner of his own life, and has the right to live his life in any manner he chooses as long as he does not violate the rights of others.<br>
&quot;<br>
Houman Shadab, Berkeley<br>
<br>
This is the commonly held definition and even argument of capitalism from one of the leading authorities in the field.<br>
<br>
Now its very apparent that there is an political and economic segment of each, having said that to define socialism as anything but PRIMARILY a social system is rather asinine and to define capitalism as anything but primarily a economic system is also asinine. While I really don't like to bring in definitions because I think they only make the issues far less clear, this is the stance from which I make my statements.<br>
<br>
As for your example of competition breeding excellence, its not valid, as you provide no counterpoint. Show me a situation where there is a single provider of washing machines in some area and the combination of product quality/service/price are inferior to what you received and you MIGHT have even a miniscule point.<br>
<br>
In general course in fact I could point out the waste inherent in your system, in a socialist system whereby a single provider of washing machines could theoretically gather the best designers, workers, and distributors for there product while taking advantage of the economies of scale and it becomes quite apparent that at least in theory without exception the most potentially advantageous system to all is a communistic philosophy.<br>
<br>
PS. however that I argue this point only as a potential counterpoint and don't really belive in its validity as an absolute.<br>
