<br>
On to your points..<br>
<br>
I did not cite the following definition of socialism in my post --<br>
&quot;The stage in Marxist-Leninist theory intermediate between capitalism and communism, in which collective ownership of the economy under the dictatorship of the proletariat has not yet been successfully achieved.&quot; -- because it has disparaging overtones, and would bring marx's silly ideas about predicting stages of history into the debate.  Also, proposing that socialism is a mere prelude to communism would be silly, as this discussion is concerned with socialism and capitalism as ends.  <br>
<br>
As for the second definition I didn't cite, it is vague to the point of nonsensicality.  It deals more with the colloquial use and history of the word than its actual meaning.<br>
<br>
My point was:  socialism, as a political system, has sufficiently drastic economic ramifications to allow it to be brought into a discussion of economics.  Moreover, the economic results of socialism are clearly different in character from those of capitalism; it is not stupid or ignorant to compare and contrast the two systems, as you stated.  The two, in many ways, are in direct opposition to each other.<br>
<br>
Cerios:  &quot;While I really don't like to bring in definitions because I think they only make the issues far less clear, this is the stance from which I make my statements.&quot;<br>
<br>
The issues, if they aren't defined, can't be argued at all.  If there are no agreed upon meanings signified by the words we use, we're just a bunch of animals chattering nonsense at each other.<br>
<br>
Cerios: &quot;As for your example of competition breeding excellence, its not valid, as you provide no counterpoint. Show me a situation where there is a single provider of washing machines in some area and the combination of product quality/service/price are inferior to what you received and you MIGHT have even a miniscule point.&quot;<br>
<br>
I have an example, if not exactly a counterpoint.  Last year I wanted to buy cable internet.  I did, from one of the largest telecommunications firms in the US.  They were the only company offering cable internet in my area. <br>
<br>
After handling the installation shoddily, on numerous occasions they overbilled me.  I would call their lousy customer service department, and have my call routed to rude people in five different departments (none of whom seemed to have any idea what was going on, nor any interest in solving my problem -- they just wanted me out of their hair).  Finally I would get irate and ask to speak to a supervisor.  The supervisor would say, ok, I have fixed your problem, it's corrected in the computer sytem.  Don't worry.<br>
<br>
The next month I would get a bill with even more errors.  I'd call them back, say &quot;I talked to so-and-so who said this would be fixed?  Why are these erroneous charges still on my bill?&quot;  They would deny even having a record of my previous call, or in the rare case they did have a record of it, they would would say something like, &quot;humm... guess it didn't go through... weird...&quot; and transfer me to another friggn department.  No progress was made until I moved away and didn't have to deal with the losers anymore.<br>
<br>
DSL wasn't offered in my area.  It was dealing with this company or going back to 56k.  I can't tell you how many times I wished there was someone else to take my business to.  They did not deserve my dollar in the least.  I am certain that if they had more competition, they would not get away with treating their customers as they do.  Or if they did get away with it, one could take one's business elsewhere and not bother with them anyway.<br>
<br>
A service such as this company, but run by the socialist government, would no doubt be the same (or worse, because their position would be assured -- under capitalism, another company eventually offering cable internet is at least a possibility; thus it would be reckless for them not to try to please customers at all). <br>
<br>
Everyone knows government agencies are prone to bloated bureaucracy.  Without having anything to compete against, nor any worries about recourse from the consumer, they would have even less incentive to maintain a high standard of quality than the aforementioned company, which sucked donkey dong.<br>
<br>
